The male and female fruit flies have the alleles $(R, W)$, so the possible alleles they can pass to their offspring are $R$ or $W$. Thus, the possible genotypes of the offspring are $RR$, $RW$, $WR$, and $WW$, where $RW$ and $WR$ are genetically equivalent.

## Step 2: Calculate the probability of each genotype.
Since each parent has an equal chance of passing either $R$ or $W$, the probability of each genotype is as follows:
- $P(RR) = P(R \text{ from male}) \times P(R \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
- $P(RW) = P(R \text{ from male}) \times P(W \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
- $P(WR) = P(W \text{ from male}) \times P(R \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
- $P(WW) = P(W \text{ from male}) \times P(W \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
Since $RW$ and $WR$ are equivalent, $P(RW \text{ or } WR) = 0.25 + 0.25 = 0.5$.

## Step 3: Determine the probability that an offspring has white eyes.
An offspring will have white eyes if it has either $WW$ or $RW/WR$. Thus, $P(\text{white eyes}) = P(WW) + P(RW \text{ or } WR) = 0.25 + 0.5 = 0.75$.

## Step 4: Calculate the conditional probability that an offspring has two white alleles given that its eyes are white.
The conditional probability is given by $P(WW | \text{white eyes}) = \frac{P(WW)}{P(\text{white eyes})} = \frac{0.25}{0.75}$.

## Step 5: Evaluate the conditional probability to a numeric value.
$P(WW | \text{white eyes}) = \frac{0.25}{0.75} = 0.3333...$, which rounds to $0.33$ when rounded to two significant figures.

The final answer is $0.33$.
