## Step 1: Calculate the energy of a single UV photon
To find the energy of a single UV photon, we use the formula $E = \frac{hc}{\lambda}$, where $h$ is Planck's constant ($6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J s}$), $c$ is the speed of light ($3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}$), and $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the photon. Given $\lambda = 300 \, \text{nm} = 300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m}$, we can substitute these values into the formula.

## Step ## Step 2: Perform the calculation for the energy of a single photon
$E = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J s}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s})}{300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m}} = \frac{19.878 \times 10^{-26} \, \text{J m}}{300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}$.

## Step ## Step 3: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons
To find the energy of one mole of UV photons, we multiply the energy of a single photon by Avogadro's number ($6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}$). So, $E_{\text{mole}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}) = 3.991 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}$.

## Step ## Step 4: Convert the energy from J/mol to kJ/mol
To convert the energy from $\text{J/mol}$ to $\text{kJ/mol}$, we divide by 1000 since $1 \, \text{kJ} = 1000 \, \text{J}$. Thus, $E_{\text{mole}} = \frac{3.991 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}}{1000} = 399.1 \, \text{kJ/mol}$.

## Step ## Step 5: Compare the energy with the typical single-bond energy
The energy of one mole of UV photons is $399.1 \, \text{kJ/mol}$, and the typical single-bond energy is given as $400 \, \text{kJ/mol}$. The calculated energy is very close to the single-bond energy.

